Abstract



Past research has been surprisingly mixed in its conclusions about the relationship between group identification and group norm following. Equally, it has left unaddressed a key issue: how does this relationship change and evolve over the course of group membership? The present research used online discussion forums to monitor the evolution of such relationships. Participants comprised one hundred ninety-eight forum users who responded to an online questionnaire invitation posted on the forum. The questionnaire assessed length of their engagement on the forum; levels of identification with the forum group; and tendency to engage in normative behaviour. Higher levels of social identification strongly predicted both enthusiasm about and adherence to group norms. These relationships strengthened, rather than dissipated, with increased density of forum use. We discuss the implications of these findings for theories of social influence and social capital; online sociability and well being; and change in the self across time.

This talk alerted academics to some of the practical aspects of group identity (here, in terms of how it was linked in a positive sense to well-being and to offline involvement). It was clear that the audience (as is often the case) do not always readily apply the theoretical aspects to practical applications. What was also noteworthy is that the audience were reminded of the role traditional forums can still play, and how, in the rush to embrace newer forms of social media (Facebook, Twitter), we ought not to overlook the merits of these older formats.

After my talk, several academics requested copies of our draft manuscript.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>r-6018066542.2399222b180888</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Other academic audiences (collaborators, peers etc.)</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://abstracts.bps.org.uk/index.cfm?&amp;ResultsType=Abstracts&amp;ResultSet_ID=7187&amp;FormDisplayMode=view&amp;frmShowSelected=true&amp;localAction=details</gtr:url><gtr:year>2011</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Understanding and harnessing the power of online communities</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>International</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>9A694FF1-3B3B-4489-B7D1-422840DCC92C</gtr:id><gtr:impact>In addition to the seminar presented at the one day conference as part of the South West Forum's (SWF) programme of events (reported as separate outcome) we also filmed a shorter, 'Talking Heads' video in which Louise Pendry and Jessica Salvatore summarised the rationale, research and main findings more concisely. The purpose of this shorter version was to promote a wider dissemination of our main findings.



